{[%evp 0,29,19,19,19,-9,-4,-4,6,10,42,42,57,57,57,57,57,57,66,55,51,52,46,28,27,-15,-11,0,11,9,-5,-26] Welcome to the second part of the series on the Queen's Gambit Declined. In this course, we will be covering the following topics- Vienna with ...dxc4-Bb4/b5, The Semi-Tarrasch with ...Nxd5, The Semi-Tarrasch with ...cxd4, QGD 4...Nbd7 & QGD 4...h6 for White. Let me take you through the key positions that will be a part of this course.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 {The starting point of this course. Black now has plenty of alternatives.} c5 {with this move, black challenges our centre. This move may lead to the Semi-Tarrasch variations with 5.Cxd5 cxd4 or 5...Nxd5. Black may also play 5...exd5 and opt for the Tarrasch system.} (4... dxc4 {is called the Vienna variation. Black wins a pawn but gives up the centre. The most challenging move in the position is to play} 5. e4 {gaining space and threatening Bxc4. Black now has two important ways to deal with this.} Bb4 {the main move by far. Black pins the knight and threatens ...Nxe4.} ({a modern approach to this position is to play} 5... b5 {[%cal Rc3b5,Rf6e4] looking to meet Nxb5 with ...Nxe4. Here, we can go for} 6. e5 Nd5 7. Nxb5 {[%csl Rc4] which black typically responds with} Nb6 {[%cal Gb6c4] defending the c4-pawn. Black wants to establish control over the light squares in this position with Bb7. Here, my recommendation is to finish our development with} 8. Be2 Nc6 9. Be3 Be7 {followed by the strong prophylactic move} 10. a3 {[%cal Gd1c2,Ga1d1,Yh2h4,Rf3g5] with the intention of playing Qc2-Rd1 next. We may then castle and play against the weaknesses on c4/e4/c5, or initiate a kingside attack with h4/Ng5. White remains slightly better in these positions.}) 6. Bxc4 Nxe4 {we are not afraid of losing the pawn; in fact, we give up a second pawn with} 7. O-O {our claim in such positions that our lead in development and the space advantage compensate for the missing pawn. Black now has two important options, ...Nxc3 and ...Nf6.} Nxc3 (7... Nf6 {is the more defensive approach. However, after} 8. Qa4+ Nc6 9. Ne5 {we can recollect the lost pawn and keep some initiative in the process.} Rb8 {runs into} (9... Bd6 {runs into} 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Qxc6+ Bd7 12. Qf3 $14 {where white remains due to the better pawn structure and the extra space in the centre.}) 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Qxa7 {where white is better due to the pawn structure and the outside passed pawn.}) 8. bxc3 Be7 {the main response. The main move for White in such positions is Ne5, but I recommend going for the rarer} (8... Bd6 {is a possible alternative, but after} 9. Ng5 h6 10. Qh5 O-O 11. Ne4 {White is exerting serious pressure on the kingside/centre.}) (8... Bxc3 $4 {is a blunder as white can play} 9. Rb1 {[%cal Gb1b3,Gf3g5,Gb3h3] bringing the rook into the attack with Rb3-Ng5-Rh3 next.}) 9. Qe2 $5 O-O 10. Rd1 $5 {where black struggles due to the lack of space and piece activity.}) (4... Nbd7 {With Nbd7, black wants to get a QGD/ a Ragozin without Qa4+ lines. My recommendation here is to play} 5. Qc2 $5 {a rare, but a strong move. We are being prophylactic against black's idea of ...Bb4.} dxc4 {the critical response. Here my recommendation is to gain space in the centre with} (5... c5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Nxd5 exd5 8. e3 Bd6 9. b3) (5... Bb4 {is met with} 6. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2] where white has a much better version of the Catalan. White won a comfortable game in 1-0 (65) Abdusattorov,N (2716)-Erigaisi,A (2712) Hangzhou 2023}) (5... c6 {can be met with 6.e3, which transposes to the Meran variation. This was covered in Part I of the series.} 6. e3) (5... Be7 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bf4 {gives us a better version of the typical QGD lines. We are going to play h3-e3 & Bd3 next.}) 6. e4 {which black typically responds by striking our centre with} c5 {After} 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 {we reach a position which has occurred very rarely but has been mostly tried by top-level players. White keeps good chances for an initiative here.}) (4... h6 {the idea of this is to stop us from playing ...Bg5. However, as we have seen plenty of times already, I recommend you to go for} 5. Bf4 {structures in the QGD.} (5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 Bd6 {is what black was hoping for. With 5.Bf4 we keep a bit more flexibility.}) {here, the crucial response is} 5... Bd6 {where we can go for the extremely rare} 6. Qc1 $5 {with the idea of meeting} O-O 7. g4 $5 {With great attacking prospects. White managed to win in the following game. 1-0 (56) Sarana,A (2693)-Svane,R (2641) Chess.com INT 2023}) 5. cxd5 Nxd5 {is the traditional Semi-Tarrasch. Black gives up the control of the centre to exchange some pieces. The critical position arises after} (5... exd5 {the Tarrasch variation. For this, I recommend to enter the sharp variation with} 6. Bg5 $1 {the critical situation arises after} Be6 7. e3 c4 8. Be2 Bb4 9. O-O O-O 10. Ne5 $5 {where black has two important moves} Qa5 {the most natural. Here the novel} (10... Nbd7 {is met with} 11. Bf3 {[%csl Rd5] where we keep some pressure thanks to the weakness on d5.}) 11. f4 $5 $146 {leads to a very sharp game with} Bxc3 12. f5 $5 Bd7 13. bxc3 {where black needs to be extremely accurate, to survive.}) (5... cxd4 {is the modern way of playing. Black wants to 'kill' the game. However, this allows us to get a risk-free position. My recommendation is to play against the Isolated pawn with} 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 $5 {after} Be7 8. e3 O-O 9. Be2 h6 10. Bh4 Nc6 11. Qd3 {we reach an important branching point. Black has two plays of playing this position} Qb6 {the most played response.} (11... Be6 {is met with} 12. O-O Qb6 {where after} 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nxd5 {where black needs to defend against an unpleasant attack.}) {here I recommend going for} 12. O-O {which Black typically meets with} Rd8 {after} 13. Rfd1 {Black again has two important moves.} Be6 {the most natural, and the most played move.} (13... Qxb2 {has been tried by some players, but after} 14. Rab1 Qa3 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nxd5 Qxd3 17. Nxf6+ {Black has to end up defending a horrendous pawn structure.}) {and here the move} 14. Nb5 $1 {poses good practical problems.}) 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O {and here I recommend the extremely rare, but practically testing,} 11. h4 $5 {with this move, white retains flexibility between Bd3/Bc4. The most logical sequence here is} b6 {where I recommend going for} 12. Rd1 Bb7 13. Bd3 {Black now has two important choices.} Nd7 {is met with} (13... Nc6 {is met with} 14. Qe3 $14 {where White retains some edge due to the enormous space advantage and the potential to attack on the kingside.}) 14. O-O Nf6 15. Qf4 $146 {[%cal Ge4e5,Rd4d5] with the threat of playing d5/e5 next White has chances to get an attack or a passed pawn in the centre.} *

