{Welcome to the first chapter. We will begin by examining the Tarrasch variation.} 1. d4 d5 (1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 exd5 {is another way to reach the same position.}) 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 exd5 {the starting point of the chapter. Black accepts an isolated pawn in the centre of the board hoping to have enough activity to compensate for the structural defect. I recommend going for the direct} 6. Bg5 {[%csl Rd5] putting pressure on the d5 pawn immediately.} ({the main move for white in these positions is} 6. g3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf1g2]}) 6... Be6 {the only critical response.} ({the other moves are significantly weaker. For example,} 6... Be7 {runs into} 7. dxc5 $1 $14) (6... cxd4 $6 {is inferior too as after} 7. Bxf6 ({or} 7. Nxd4 $14) 7... Qxf6 8. Nxd5 Qd8 9. Qxd4 $14 {white keeps a risk-free edge.}) 7. e3 {[%cal Gf1b5]} c4 {Black's best bet. This stops us from playing Bd3 and kills off all the possibilities of opening the d-file with dxc5.} ({the most played move in the position is} 7... Nc6 {but after} 8. Bb5 $16 {White has a significant advantage. We want to follow up with normal moves like dxc5-Rc1-0-0 next. A possible sequence can be} Be7 (8... a6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Qa4 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Rc5,Rc6][%cal Gd4c5,Ga1c1,Gf3d4]}) 9. dxc5 $1 Bxc5 10. O-O $16 {[%csl Rc6,Rd5,Rf6,Gg5][%cal Ga1c1,Gd1a4,Gf1d1]}) (7... a6 $6 8. Be2 Nc6 9. dxc5 $14 {[%csl Rd5,Rf6][%cal Gg5f6] the issue of the isolated pawn still persists in black's position.}) 8. Be2 {we develop our bishop normally. Black's best move in the position is to play} Bb4 (8... Be7 {is slightly inferior. After} 9. O-O {[%cal Gb2b3] we will break open the Queenside with b3 next.} O-O 10. Bxf6 $1 {[%csl Rd5]} Bxf6 11. b3 Qa5 $5 (11... cxb3 12. Qxb3 {[%csl Rb7,Rd5,Rf6][%cal Gf1c1] gives us our dream position. Both of Black's bishops are inactive, while white has obvious targets on d5/b7 to hit.}) 12. Qd2 Nc6 13. bxc4 dxc4 14. Rab1 Rab8 15. Rb5 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Gd4,Ge3][%cal Gf1b1,Ge3e4] white has obvious pressure thanks to the activity of the pieces and the mobile pawn mass in the centre.}) (8... Nc6 9. O-O Be7 {has been tried by some players, but after} 10. b3 Qa5 (10... cxb3 11. Qxb3 $16 {[%csl Rb7]}) 11. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 12. Rc1 cxb3 13. Qxb3 $14 {[%csl Gb3,Rb7,Gc3,Rd5,Re6,Rf6] white keeps the typical advantage.}) (8... Nbd7 9. Ne5 Bb4 10. O-O {transposes}) 9. O-O O-O (9... Nbd7 10. Ne5 {should transpose with ...0-0. The only independent try is} Qa5 {but after} 11. Nxd7 Nxd7 12. Qc2 O-O 13. a3 $1 Bd6 14. f4 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf4f5,Ge2f3,Gb2b3] white has a clear advantage. We plan to push f5/put pressure on d5/open up the Queenside with b3 next.}) 10. Ne5 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf2f4,Ye2f3,Gf3d5] the most ambitious move in the position. With this move, we bring our knight to the most active square and prepare to further gain space with f4. We might even play Bf3 in some positions and increase the attack over the d5-pawn.} Qa5 {the most challenging response. Black steps out of the pin and threatens ...Bxc3-Ne4.} (10... h6 {allows us to spoil the pawn structure on the kingside with} 11. Bxf6 gxf6 (11... Qxf6 12. f4 $16 {[%csl Gd4,Rd5,Gf4][%cal Gf4f5,Ge2f3] white stands better because of the humungous space advantage and the pressure over the d5-pawn. We are threatening to play f5/Bf3 next.}) 12. Nf3 $14 {[%csl Rd5,Rf6,Rh6][%cal Ge3e4]}) (10... Nbd7 {is covered in the next chapter.}) 11. f4 $5 $146 {[%cal Gf4f5] this novelty poses a lot of concrete problems for Black. The immediate threat is f5-Bxf6.} (11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Ng4 Nd7 {[%cal Gf6f5,Gd7f6] is the strategic justification behind black's play. Black wants to play f5-Nf6 next.}) 11... Bxc3 {the only move that makes sense. Otherwise f5 is crushing.} 12. f5 $1 {an important intermezzo.} (12. bxc3 Ne4 {leads to a reasonable position for black.}) 12... Bc8 $1 {the strongest move for Black. This is very hard to play in a practical game.} (12... Bxb2 {isn't great and after} 13. fxe6 fxe6 14. Rb1 $18 {White has a decisive advantage.}) (12... Bd7 {[%csl Rf7] is the position's most 'human' move. However, after} 13. bxc3 Ne4 {it seems is taking over, but white has the important intermezzo with} 14. Be7 $1 Re8 {and now we solve the issue of the pawn on c3 with} (14... Nxc3 $4 15. Qd2 {[%csl Ra5]} Nxe2+ 16. Qxe2 $18 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Ge2g4,Gf5f6,Re5d7]}) 15. Bb4 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gb4c3] defending the c3 pawn. Black now has to go for} Qc7 {where we continue to build the initiative with} 16. Bf3 {threatening Bxe4 and a subsequent attack on the kingside with Nxf7/f6/Qh5.} Nf6 {but now white has a stunning resource with} (16... a5 {is possible but after} 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Ba3 $40 {[%cal Gd1h5,Gf1f4,Gf4h4] White keeps a huge initiative.}) 17. g4 $1 h6 18. Nxf7 $3 {[%csl Ra8,Rb8] exploiting the lack of development on the Queenside. After} Kxf7 19. g5 hxg5 20. Bxd5+ Nxd5 21. Qh5+ Kg8 22. f6 {White has a decisive attack. Few sample lines-} Nxf6 23. Rxf6 {[%cal Ga1f1]} Ba4 $3 {the only move to remain in the game.} (23... gxf6 24. Qg6+ Kh8 25. Qxf6+ Kh7 26. Qf7+ $18 {[%cal Ga1f1,Gf1f6]}) 24. Raf1 gxf6 25. Rxf6 Qg7 26. Rg6 Nd7 27. Qxg5 Qxg6 28. Qxg6+ $18) 13. bxc3 Ne4 14. Be7 $1 Re8 ({another interesting try is} 14... Qxc3 15. Bxf8 Qxe3+ 16. Kh1 Kxf8 {where black claims some compensation, but White has the strong} 17. Bxc4 $1 {[%cal Gd1h5] at his disposal. After} Nf2+ 18. Rxf2 Qxf2 19. Qh5 Qxf5 20. Qh4 $14 {[%cal Ga1f1,Rh4d8] we retain some advantage thanks to the attacking prospects.}) 15. Bb4 Qc7 {[%cal Gc7f7] this time, black has the f7-square covered!} 16. Bf3 Nf6 {[#]} (16... Bxf5 $4 17. Bxe4 Bxe4 18. Rxf7 $18) (16... a5 $4 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Ba3 $18 {is even stronger this time with the bishop being on c8.}) {We cannot open up the position with g4 anymore, but we can go for} 17. e4 $1 {with good chances.} (17. g4 $6 h6 {[%cal Ge5f7,Rc7f7] unlike the line with ...Bd7, we don't have the possibility of Nxf7 anymore!}) 17... Nc6 $1 {this concrete move is the best response for Black.} (17... dxe4 18. Bh5 $18 {leads to a decisive attack.} Rxe5 19. dxe5 Qxe5 20. Qd8+ Qe8 21. Qxe8+ Nxe8 22. Be2 Nc6 23. Bxc4 $18) (17... a5 18. Ba3 Nc6 19. Nxc6 dxe4 20. Ne5 exf3 21. Qxf3 $36 {[%cal Rg2g4,Ga1e1] white retains good chances thanks to the attacking prospects.} Bd7 22. Rae1 $1 $16) 18. Nxc6 {[%cal Ge4e5]} dxe4 {We can now try} 19. Ne7+ $5 {black is forced to give up an exchange with} (19. Ne5 exf3 20. Qxf3 Bd7 $1 $11 {[%cal Gd7c6]}) 19... Rxe7 20. Bxe7 Qxe7 21. Be2 {where black needs to the concrete} b5 $1 (21... Bd7 22. Bxc4 Rc8 23. Qb3 $1 $16) 22. a4 Bd7 23. Qb1 $1 bxa4 (23... a6 {is a blunder as after} 24. axb5 Bxb5 25. Qxb5 $3 axb5 26. Rxa8+ Ne8 27. Re1 $18 {[%cal Ge2f3] white has a decisive advantage.}) 24. Bd1 $14 {we keep some practical pull here but black is fine objectively.} *

