{[%evp 0,41,19,34,32,-12,-11,0,6,6,44,44,46,23,54,34,30,16,30,34,41,20,29,-27,-39,-35,-34,-21,-35,10,44,58,39,51,-28,13,14,9,45,21,7,5,46,33]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 Be6 7. e3 c4 8. Be2 Bb4 9. O-O O-O 10. Ne5 Nbd7 {the starting point of this chapter. Black develops another piece and prepares ...Qa5 without spoiling the pawn structure after Bxf6. Here, I recommend going for} 11. Bf3 $5 {[%csl Rd5] putting pressure on the pawn on d5.} (11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. Bxf6 gxf6 {[%csl Gb4,Ge6][%cal Gb7b5,Ga7a5] doesn't give much in my opinion. Black will start rolling the pawns on the Queenside.}) 11... Qa5 {here we can go for} 12. Nxd7 Nxd7 13. Qc2 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb2b3,Ge3e4] where we keep two plans. We want to open the Queenside with b3 or open up the centre with e4.} h6 $1 {this help black win an extra tempo.} (13... Rfe8 {has been tried by some players, but after} 14. a3 Be7 (14... Bxc3 15. bxc3 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Rd5,Gf3,Gg5][%cal Ga3a4,Gf1b1]}) 15. Bxe7 Rxe7 16. b3 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Rd5,Re6][%cal Gc2b3,Gf1c1,Gc3e2,Ge2f4] white keeps a simple edge.}) 14. Bh4 Rfe8 15. h3 $1 $146 {[%cal Gf1e1,Yb2b3] this prophylactic move is quite strong. We are waiting for black to commit to a plan. We keep the options of pushing e4 or b3 alive.} ({also possible was} 15. a3 Be7 16. Bxe7 Rxe7 17. b3 cxb3 18. Qxb3 Nf6 19. Ne2 Rc8 20. h3 $5) 15... Nb6 {Black's best bet. Black prepares Bxc3-Na4-b5.} (15... Rac8 {is met with the thematic} 16. Rfe1 {[%cal Ge3e4] intending e4. After} Nb6 17. a3 Bxc3 18. bxc3 Na4 19. Rac1 {[%cal Ge3e4] white is in time to push e4 on the next move.}) 16. Rfc1 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gc2c3] We want to play a3 Bxc3 Qxc3 Rxc3 to preserve our Queenside pawn structure.} Bd6 $1 {Black knows a3 is coming so he is withdrawing voluntarily.} (16... Rac8 17. Bg3 {[%cal Ga2a3] we are in time to push a3-b3 on the next move.}) (16... Bxc3 {is a bit premature. After} 17. bxc3 Na4 {white has the important resource} 18. Rab1 $1 b6 19. Rb4 $14) 17. a3 {We play it regardless and keep control of the b4 square. Now that black has fully diverted the attention on the Queenside, we can also try to gain space on the kingside!} Bd7 {Black is putting his pieces on squares where the pieces are good after the b3 break. We can, therefore, switch our plan and go for} (17... Rac8 18. Rf1 $1 {[%cal Ga1e1] is quite similar to the text}) 18. Rf1 $1 {[%cal Ga1e1,Ge3e4,Gf2f4,Gf3d1] preparing Rae1-Bd1 & e4/f4!} Bc6 {Black is getting in best possible shape for e4} (18... Rac8 19. Rae1 $14 {[%cal Gf3d1,Ye3e4,Yf2f3]}) (18... Ba4 {looks natural, but after} 19. Qf5 $1 g6 20. Qb1 {[%cal Gb1e1,Rc3d5,Yc3a4]} Bc6 21. Qc2 {[%csl Rg6] we keep the same ideas of Rae1-Bd1-e4 but with an extra hook on g6.}) 19. Rae1 Rac8 (19... Na4 20. Bxd5 $1 Nxc3 21. Bxc6 bxc6 22. bxc3 Qxa3 23. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5,Ge1e3,Ge3g3,Gf2f4] White keeps a dangerous initiative.}) 20. Bg4 $1 Rc7 21. f3 $16 {[%cal Ge3e4] we are in time to push e4 next, after which we keep a huge attack.} *

