1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 {the branching point from the previous chapter. This variation is quite fashionable recently. This has been the preference of players looking to kill the game with Black. Nevertheless, the position is not entirely without demerits for Black. Firstly, black is strategically worse in almost every single variation. If, by any chance, black forgets a line, they can get in deep trouble. Secondly, in almost all lines, white is not under any kind of risk whatsoever. So, you'll probably have a risk-free edge in most positions.} 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 {my choice. This keeps more chances to get a game} ({the other choice for white players is to play} 7. e4 Nc6 8. Bb5 dxe4 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Ng5 Be6 $5 {the lines here are more concrete in nature. However, if black has good memory, it is very hard to get something tangible here.}) 7... Be7 8. e3 O-O (8... Nc6 9. Qd3 O-O 10. Be2 {transposes to the main line of the text.}) 9. Be2 {we aim to finish our development and put pressure on d5 next.} Nc6 {the most played move.} (9... h6 {is covered in Chapter 5.}) 10. Qd3 {and now black has some interesting choices.} h6 {the most played move.} ({starting with} 10... Be6 {is also quite possible. We play the natural} 11. O-O {and finish our development. Black's critical response here is} Qb6 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gf8d8,Ga8c8] where I recommend going for} 12. a3 $1 {the smartest try in my opinion.} (12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Nxd5 $5 {is very similar to the variation covered in Chapter 5.}) 12... h6 (12... Rfd8 {is possible. We need to enter the forced sequence with} 13. b4 d4 14. Na4 $1 Qc7 15. exd4 {where it seems like we are up a pawn, but after} Ng4 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Gc6d4] black recovers the pawn. After} 16. Bxe7 Nxd4 17. g3 Nxe2+ 18. Qxe2 Qxe7 19. Nc5 $14 {we will take on e6 next, after which we keep an edge due to the better pawn structure.}) 13. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gc3a4] the point. Black's queen is under duress} (13. Bh4 Rfd8 $11 {[%cal Gd5d4]}) 13... Nh5 {[%csl Rf4]} (13... Rfd8 14. b4 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc3a4]}) (13... Rac8 14. b4 $14) 14. Be5 $1 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Nf6 16. Nf3 Bd6 17. Rfd1 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Rd5][%cal Gf3d4] we remain due to the weaknesses on d5/d4.}) (10... Qb6 {another possible try is} 11. O-O Rd8 {but after} 12. Qb5 Qxb5 13. Nxb5 $14 {[%csl Rd5] we keep an edge.}) 11. Bh4 Qb6 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gf8d8,Rb6b2]} 12. O-O Rd8 {Black's main response in the position. With ...Rd8, Black also keeps the possibility of pushing ...d4 later in the game.} (12... Be6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nxd5 {transposes to chapter 5.}) 13. Rfd1 {Black now has two important alternatives} Be6 {This move is considered fine by engines but after the move} (13... Qxb2 {is covered in the next chapter.}) 14. Nb5 $1 {[%cal Gb5d4] white keeps some practical pressure.} Rac8 {the most played move.} (14... Bg4 $5 $146 {is met with} 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Ne5 {and it seems like black is able to rupture our kingside after} 17. Qb3 Nxf3+ {but in fact with} 18. gxf3 {[%csl Rd5,Rf6][%cal Ga1c1,Gb5d4,Gh4e7] we continue to keep the pressure on. The d5 pawn is still weak, while with Rac1 coming in next, white will have a much easier game. White's weaknesses on kingside are not easy to attack, while the d5 pawn is always a target. If required, we can play Nd4 to offer a trade of Queens.} Rac8 19. Nd4 Qxb3 20. Nxb3 g5 21. Bg3 $14 {[%csl Rd5,Rf7][%cal Gg3e5,Ge5c3]}) (14... a6 15. Nbd4 Nxd4 {was tried by Sadhwani. After} 16. Nxd4 g5 17. Bg3 Ne4 {and now} 18. Be5 $1 $146 {[%cal Ge2f3] threatening Bf3, white keeps an edge due to the weakened King and the pawn structure.} (18. Bf3 {0-1 (34) Lazavik,D (2553)-Sadhwani,R (2603) Chess.com INT 2023})) 15. Nbd4 {White's point. We know we have the dream setup against the IQP.} Bd7 {computer's top choice. Black calmly retreats.} (15... Bg4 $146 {is still possible. The most testing attempt seems to be the ending after} 16. h3 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Nxd4 18. Qxd4 Qxd4 19. Rxd4 Rc2 20. Rb1 {[%cal Gf3d1] where we will to grind out the position thanks to the advantage of the pair of bishops and the weak pawn on d5.}) ({another natural option for Black is to play} 15... Nxd4 16. Nxd4 g5 {with the thematic} 17. Bg3 Ne4 {in mind. However, after} 18. Be5 $1 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5] white keeps some typical pressure.}) 16. h3 {[%cal Gh4g3,Yg3h2] creating an escape square for the bishop.} Re8 $1 {this unusual move is the cleanest equalizer for Black. This was also played in the only corr. game in this position.} (16... g5 {is met with} 17. Bg3 Ne4 18. Nxc6 bxc6 19. Be5 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Rd5,Rf7,Rh6][%cal Ga1c1,Gf3d2]}) {I recommend going for} 17. Rab1 $5 $146 {maintaining the pressure. White has a static pressure, so black now has two principled ways to play the position.} Nxd4 (17... g5 $5 18. Bg3 Ne4 {is also possible. Here I recommend going for the typical} 19. Nxc6 bxc6 20. Be5 {but black has the extra resource of} h5 {[%cal Gg5g4] White's best bet to counter this is by playing} 21. Qc2 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf3d2,Gd2e4] threatening to trade the active knight subsequently with Nd2.} Bf5 (21... g4 22. hxg4 hxg4 23. Nd2 $5) 22. Bd3 {[%csl Gd3,Ge5][%cal Gf3d2]}) 18. Nxd4 g5 19. Bg3 Ne4 20. Bh2 {[%csl Rf5,Rh6][%cal Gd3b3,Ye2g4] we will follow up with Qb3 or Bg4 next. Do not be afraid about ...Rc2 (after ...Qxb3 Nxb3) in such lines as after Bd3, the rook has nothing better than going back. You also keep the idea of pushing f3 and then going for Nd4 again in those positions.} *

