{[%evp 0,65,20,21,21,6,19,7,20,20,28,41,44,41,40,29,27,17,17,23,14,14,19,19,28,27,27,27,38,44,81,57,53,48,67,36,61,54,58,59,59,32,54,42,42,38,37,15,32,34,34,35,50,34,9,0,0,12,23,0,0,26,19,68,170,0,85,105]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Bg5 Be7 8. e3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. Qd3 h6 11. Bh4 Qb6 12. O-O Rd8 13. Rfd1 {the starting point of this chapter. Instead of ...Be6, black has two other reasonable options.} Qxb2 {the main move of this chapter. This has been the trusted weapon of Wesley So.} ({a weaker of playing in the same spirit is} 13... g5 $143 14. Bg3 Qxb2 {however, after} 15. Rab1 Qa3 {we have the extra option of playing} 16. Rb3 $1 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gh2h4] followed by h4 at the right time.} Qc5 (16... Qa5 17. Qb1 a6 18. h4 $1 $14 {[%csl Rc8] black has issues with development of the c8-bishop and the weaknesses on the Queenside.}) 17. Nd4 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Rd8d1] a smart prophylactic move against ...Ne4. We are all set to push h4 next.} (17. h4 Ne4 $1) 17... Bf8 18. h4 $14) 14. Rab1 Qa3 15. Bxf6 $5 {This forces liquidation to an equal ending but where white keeps significant chances due to the better pawn structure. The critical line arises after} (15. Rb3 Qa5 $5 {doesn't offer much as there is no target on the kingside to attack onto.}) 15... Bxf6 16. Nxd5 {where black has two important choices} Qxd3 $6 (16... Qxa2 {is another possibility. We can respond by playing} 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 {and now play the important} 18. Nd4 {stopping Black from trading the rooks. White keeps a pleasant game due to the attacking prospects on the kingside. Black's play is not easy.} Be6 $1 {[%cal Gd8d6,Ga8d8] sacrificing a pawn to include all the pieces into the game.} (18... Nxd4 19. exd4 Qd5 20. Rb5 {looks extremely dangerous for black.}) 19. Rxb7 Rd6 20. Rd2 $1 Qa1+ 21. Rb1 Qa5 22. Rbd1 $1 $146 {overprotecting d4. After} Nxd4 23. exd4 {[%csl Rf6,Rh6]} Rad8 24. h3 $11 {/+=. Black is fine objectively, but from a practical point of view, this is quite unpleasant for black. There is no forced way to kill the game and we can comfortably press on for 50 more moves.}) 17. Rxd3 Bf5 {Black's point. We are forced to trade a lot of pieces.} 18. Nxf6+ gxf6 19. Rxd8+ Nxd8 20. Rc1 $1 {the most challenging response. After the obvious} (20. Rd1 Nc6 {[%cal Gf5e6,Ga8c8,Gc6b4] looks fine for black.}) 20... Rc8 21. Rxc8 Bxc8 22. Nd4 {We reach a position that is fine for Black objectively, but white keeps great practical chances. The following moves are not forced by any means, but I wanted to include this to show some ideas in the position.} Kf8 (22... Bd7 {is another possibility. Here our most challenging move is} 23. Bb5 $1 {forcing Black to play} Be6 $1 (23... Bxb5 24. Nxb5 $16 {Knights endgames usually are quite similar to pawn endgames. White keeps excellent chances due to the broken pawn structure. You want to include your king into the game next.}) 24. a3 Kf8 {leads to positions similar to the main line after something like} 25. f4 Ke7 26. Kf2 a6 27. Be2 Kd6 28. g4 Nc6 29. h4 Nxd4 30. exd4 $5) 23. g4 Ke7 24. f4 Bd7 25. Kf2 Nc6 26. a3 Nxd4 27. exd4 b5 28. Ke3 a5 {all of these moves were natural. After} 29. h4 {the position is not easy for black to defend by any means. Black needs to show great accuracy.} Kd6 $143 $4 {runs into} (29... Bc6 $1 30. d5 $5 Bxd5 31. Bxb5 Kd6 32. Be2 {[%cal Ge3d4,Gh4h5,Gg4g5] we still keep some chances due to the threat of Kd4 followed by h5-g5 at the right time. This looks extremely dangerous for Black.}) 30. h5 $18 b4 31. axb4 axb4 32. Bf3 $18 {[%csl Gh5][%cal Ge3d3,Gd4d5,Yg4g5] with a decisive advantage. Some sample lines-} (32. Kd3 Bb5+) 32... Bc8 (32... b3 33. Kd3 Ke7 34. Kc3 Ba4 35. d5 $18 {[%cal Gc3b2,Gb2a3]}) (32... Bb5 33. d5 $1 b3 (33... Kc5 34. g5 $18) 34. Kd2 $18) 33. Kd3 $18 *

