{Welcome to the sixth chapter. In this chapter, we will be covering the 5...Nxd5 line for black.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 {the traditional 'Semi-Tarrasch'. Black gives up the entire centre to trade a couple of minor pieces. Black's claim is that he can undermine our centre later on. We don't mind this, of course, as it allows us to build a huge center and thus gives us good attacking opportunities later in the game.} 6. e4 {gaining maximum space.} Nxc3 (6... cxd4 {has been tried by a few players, but after} 7. Qxd4 $1 Nxc3 (7... Nc6 8. Bb5 $1 $16 {is an important motif.}) 8. Qxc3 $14 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gc3g7] white keeps a risk-free advantage.}) 7. bxc3 cxd4 (7... Be7 $6 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O $14 {[%csl Gc1,Re7] We don't mind keeping the bishops on the board as we have more space.}) 8. cxd4 Bb4+ (8... Nc6 {has been tried by Erigaisi, but with} 9. a3 $1 {[%csl Rf8][%cal Gf8b4,Ra3b4] we can stop black from trading bishops. We want to follow up with Bc4 next.} Be7 (9... Bd6 10. Bc4 O-O {is an inferior version of the ...Be7 line as after} 11. e5 Be7 12. h4 $1 $14 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gc4d3,Gd3h7] followed by Bd3, white has an initiative brewing up.}) 10. Bc4 b5 11. Ba2 O-O 12. O-O $14 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ga1b1,Gb1b5,Gd4d5,Ga3a4] we keep an edge due to the extra space. Our idea is to play Rb1 next, or push d5 at the right time.}) 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ (9... Qa5 $6 10. Rb1 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 {and although black has managed to trade queens, Black will find it difficult to develop the pieces on the Queenside comfortably.} O-O (12... Nc6 13. Bb5 Bd7 14. d5 $18 {[%csl Rb7]}) 13. Ke3 b6 14. Rc1 $16 {[%cal Gc1c7]}) 10. Qxd2 O-O {and here I recommend going for the rare but principled} 11. h4 $5 {with the blunt threat of gaining space on the kingside. We are delaying committing our bishop for the moment.} (11. Bc4 {is the most played move but this loses flexibility as we won't be able to play Bd3 later on.}) 11... b6 {the principled response.} (11... Nd7 12. Rd1 Nf6 13. Bd3 b6 14. O-O Bb7 {transposes.}) (11... Nc6 {is covered in the next chapter.}) (11... Qe7 {was tried by Kramnik, but after} 12. Bd3 $1 {our point behind h4 is clear. We are able to put the bishop on a better square.} Rd8 (12... b6 {gives us a better version of the main line of the chapter.}) 13. O-O e5 $5 {Kramnik's point. Here, both the players calculated} 14. d5 Bg4 {and presumed black was doing fine, but after} 15. Qg5 $1 Qxg5 16. hxg5 $1 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gd7f6,Gg5f6,Gb8d7]} Bxf3 17. gxf3 $16 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gf1c1,Ga2a4,Ga4a5] White has very good chances of converting this position.}) 12. Rd1 $5 {[%cal Gd4d5] We include our rook in the game hoping for quick d4-d5.} (12. h5 $5 {Is another interesting try. If you wish to explore this further, the following game can be a good starting point.} h6 13. Rh3 Bb7 14. Rg3 Kh8 15. Bd3 Nd7 16. Kf1 Rc8 17. Kg1 Qc7 18. e5 Qc3 19. Rd1 Bxf3 20. Qxc3 Rxc3 21. Rxf3 b5 22. Bxb5 Rxf3 23. gxf3 Nb6 24. Rc1 Nd5 25. Kh2 Kg8 26. Kg3 Rd8 27. Bd3 Nb6 28. Rd1 Kf8 29. Be4 Ke7 30. f4 f5 31. Bf3 Rc8 32. Rd3 Rc7 33. Ra3 Rd7 34. Ra6 Nc8 35. d5 exd5 36. Be2 Rc7 37. f3 Rc3 38. Ra4 Ke6 39. Kf2 Rc7 40. Ra6+ Kf7 41. Bd3 Ne7 42. Ke3 Rb7 43. a4 Rc7 44. a5 Nc6 45. Bxf5 d4+ 46. Kd2 Nb4 47. Rd6 Rc3 48. Rxd4 {1-0 (48) Giri,A (2714)-Praggnanandhaa,R (2587) Chess.com INT 2023 CBM 213 Extra [Giri,Anish]}) 12... Bb7 (12... Ba6 $143 {is significantly weaker. After} 13. Rh3 Bxf1 14. Kxf1 Nd7 15. Rg3 Kh8 16. e5 $14 {[%cal Gd2f4] White can build up an attack on the kingside.}) 13. Bd3 Nd7 14. O-O {and now black can a couple of important choices.} Rc8 {the most principled. Black brings the rook to the open file.} (14... Nf6 {a very natural attempt. However, after} 15. Qf4 $1 $14 {Black already has some practical problems.} Rc8 (15... Nh5 16. Qe3 Qe7 {is the computer's choice. However, after} 17. Rfe1 Rac8 {and now the thematic pawn sacrifice with} 18. d5 exd5 19. e5 $1 {[%cal Gg2g4] threatening g4,we keep good chances}) 16. d5 $1 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gf3d4] this thematic pawn sacrifice helps us close the diagonal for the light-squared bishop and at the same time, create an outpost for our knight on d4.} exd5 17. e5 Nh5 (17... Nd7 {is met with} 18. Qg4 $1 $14 {[%cal Gd3h7,Gg4h5,Gf3g5]} Rc6 (18... Re8 19. Rfe1 $14) 19. Bf5 Nc5 20. Nd4 $36) 18. Qe3 {[%cal Gf3g5]} Re8 19. Nd4 g6 {it seems like black is out of trouble but after} (19... Qxh4 $4 20. Bb5 Rf8 21. Nf5 $18) 20. Bb5 {[%csl Re8] black's rook is in a tight spot} Rf8 (20... Re7 21. f4 $16 {[%csl Ge5,Re7][%cal Gg2g4,Rd8h4]}) 21. e6 $1 {[%cal Gb5d7,Ge6f7,Gd7e6] the point behind Bb5.} Qe7 22. Bd7 Rc4 23. exf7+ $40) (14... h6 15. Qf4 Rc8 {transposes.}) 15. Qf4 $1 $146 {this novelty poses practical problems for Black. Black's natural replies are all met with strong responses.} (15. Rfe1 Nf6 $11) 15... Rc3 $1 {This unusual move is the computer's choice.} (15... Qf6 $143 {is weaker. After} 16. Qg3 {[%cal Ge4e5] we can follow up with either e5 or d5 based on Black's response.} Rfd8 (16... h6 17. d5 $14) 17. Rfe1 $14 {[%cal Gf3h2,Gh2g4]}) (15... Qc7 $143 {is weak too. After} 16. e5 {[%cal Gf3g5] we have good attacking chances.} Nf6 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gf6d5]} 17. Rc1 Qb8 18. Qd2 $1 {the last important move.} Nd5 (18... Nd7 19. Ng5 h6 20. Ne4 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5,Ge4d6] with Nd6/f4-f5 coming up next.}) (18... Bxf3 $4 19. exf6 $18 {[%cal Gd2g5]}) 19. Ng5 h6 20. Ne4 $16) ({one of two strong moves for Black is to play} 15... h6 {stopping Ng5. This is not so easy to understand on the board. Yet, with} 16. d5 {we keep some pressure.} exd5 17. e5 {Black needs to play the concrete} d4 $1 (17... Re8 $6 18. Rfe1 Qc7 19. Qf5 Nf8 20. Nd4 $14 {White is on top here.}) 18. Nxd4 {and now the unusual} Rc5 $3 {Yet with} 19. Nf5 Nxe5 20. Bb1 {[%csl Gb1,Gf4,Gf5,Rg7][%cal Gf4g3] we have dangerous attacking threats on the kingside. Only the concrete sequence with} Qc7 $1 (20... Qb8 21. Rd6 $14) 21. Qg3 Ng6 22. h5 Qxg3 {equalises for Black.} 23. fxg3 Ne5 24. Ne7+ Kh8 25. Rxf7 $1 Nxf7 26. Ng6+ $11) 16. Rfe1 {we include our rook into the game. After} Qc7 {Black claims that the rook is in front of the Queen, where it is better placed as it stops all Rc1 ideas. Yet with the natural} 17. Qd2 {[%cal Gd4d5] We keep some pressure. Some sample lines-} Rd8 (17... Nf6 $6 18. e5 Nd5 19. Ng5 $16) (17... h6 $5 18. d5 exd5 19. e5 {[%cal Gf3d4,Ge5e6] keeps the thematic pressure.}) 18. d5 Ne5 19. Nxe5 Qxe5 20. Qb2 $1 Qc7 21. Be2 exd5 (21... Rc2 22. Qb3 $16) 22. exd5 $14 *

