{In this chapter, we will examine the ...Nc6 setups for blackin the main line of the Semi-Tarrasch.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. h4 {the starting point. Black now has two important options.} b6 ({It is also possible to start with} 11... Nc6 {Just like with 11...b6, we can respond by playing} 12. Rd1 {[%cal Gd4d5] hinting towards d5 at the right moment. Black now has two significant choices.} Qa5 {played by GM Abdumalik. Black wants to trade the queens and enter the late middlegame/early endgame position.} (12... b6 {is another possibility. Although White cannot play Bd3, since Black has committed the knight to c6, we are happy to play} 13. Be2 {[%cal Gd4d5] in hopes of pushing d5 next.} Qd6 {[%cal Gd6b4,Yc6e5,Rd4d5] a very smart move. Black anticipates d4-d5. Instead of playing d5, we can initiate an assault on the kingside with} (13... Bb7 14. d5 $14 {gives us the dream position in these lines.}) 14. h5 $1 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gh5h6] black is forced to play} h6 15. g4 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gg4g5]} f6 {but after} 16. O-O Bb7 17. Qe3 $14 {[%cal Gd4d5,Ye4e5] we keep a pleasant position. Keep an eye out for d5/e5 breaks.}) 13. Qxa5 {We are happy to trade queens here.} Nxa5 14. Rc1 {generally speaking, we don't mind these positions if our king can reach e3. White can endlessly improve the position while Black plays the annoying waiting game.} b6 15. Bd3 Bb7 16. Kd2 Rac8 (16... Nc6 $6 {was played in the game, but after} 17. Rc3 Rfd8 18. Ke3 Nb4 19. Bc4 h6 20. Rhc1 {Harika had built a great advantage. Although she could not win the game, White got a great position out of the opening. ½-½ (33) Harika,D (2501)-Abdumalik,Z (2497) Saint Louis 2023}) 17. Ke3 $14 {[%cal Gh1d1,Gg2g4,Gf3e5,Gf2f4]}) 12. Rd1 Bb7 13. Bd3 Nc6 $5 {the deviation from the previous chapter. Black goes for the immediate assault against our center. The knight is more active here, but is also more vulnerable against the d4-d5 break.} 14. Qe3 $1 {[%cal Ge3d4,Gd3b1] , we take our queen out of the d-file with this move. After Bb1, d5 can be a big threat.} Rc8 {the critical response.} (14... Nb4 $143 {is weaker. After} 15. Bb1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ga2a3] we have a great advantage.} Ba6 {this looks tempting as black can temporarily stop us from castling, but after} (15... Rc8 16. O-O Nc2 17. Qd3 $16 {allows us to keep the centre. We are all set to push d5 at the right time.}) 16. Qa3 Qe7 17. Qa4 {[%cal Ga2a3] Black has nothing better than retreating with the bishop with} Bb7 {after} 18. a3 Nc6 19. O-O $16 {[%cal Gd4d5] White has developed completely. We will follow up with d5 next.}) 15. O-O Re8 $1 {[%cal Gd4d5,Re6d5,Ge8e3] This prophylactic move is black's best move. Black stops d5 for the time being.} (15... Nb4 $143 16. Bb1 $14 {transposes.}) ({the natural} 15... Qe7 {is met with} 16. h5 h6 17. Bb1 {[%cal Gd4d5] preparing the thematic d5 exd5 e5.} Rfd8 18. Rfe1 Na5 19. d5 $1 $14 {the right time to strike.} Nc4 (19... exd5 $2 20. e5 $18 {[%csl Gh5][%cal Ge3f4,Gf4f5] with the pawn on h5 and the Black knight away on a5, this is decisive.}) 20. Qf4 $14 {[%csl Gd5] Black cannot take on d5 comfortably and thus, we keep an advantage due to the passed pawn and space.}) 16. Bb1 Na5 17. Qf4 {[%cal Gd4d5] we step out of the e-file.} Nc4 {this is typical. Black wants to lodge the knight on d6 as a blockader. However, this time, we can induce weaknesses on the kingside with} (17... Qf6 {is met with} 18. Qg3 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gf3g5] where we are threatening e5 next. Black can be smart and try to exchange the Queens with} Qg6 {which we typically meet with} 19. Qh2 {[%csl Gb1][%cal Gd4d5] retaining the Queen. We now want to push d5.} Nc4 20. Rfe1 Nb2 21. Rd2 Nc4 22. Rde2 {[%cal Gd4d5]}) 18. Ng5 Qf6 $5 {this doesn't work now, as after} (18... f6 19. Nf3 $14 {[%csl Re6,Rf6,Rh7][%cal Gh4h5,Ge4e5] if after d5 Black decides to go for ...e5, this time we will have the additional idea of h5-Nh4-Nf5. White retains an edge.}) 19. Qg3 Qe7 20. e5 h6 21. Nh7 Kh8 22. Qf4 $40 {we can an initiative.} Red8 23. Nf6 {[%cal Gf6h5,Gd1d3]} *

