{[%evp 0,23,31,24,30,6,6,6,6,6,44,22,55,35,47,17,26,23,31,20,3,14,32,46,51,27] Welcome to the eighth chapter. In this chapter, we will cover 4...Nbd7 line for Black. This line picked up steam after Erigaisi started playing it continuously,with good results.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 $5 {With this move Black remains flexible with the f8-Bishop. Another advantage of this line is that White cannot play the desired Qa4+ against the Ragozin. Nevertheless, there are some drawbacks to this move. The knight on d7 is slightly misplaced. I recommend going for} 5. Qc2 $5 {[%cal Yf8b4,Gc2c3,Yb4c3] anticipating Bb4. This cunning move has given White excellent results. In this chapter, we will cover 5...c5, 5...c6, 5...a6, 5...Be7 & 5...Bd6.} c5 {the most challenging move in this chapter. Black strikes the centre immediately.} ({with this move, Black is hoping to transpose to the Semi-Slav variation. While that is a perfectly reasonable response, another interesting try is} 5... c6 6. e4 $5 {this has been tried by Bluebaum in more than 10 games! White gains space. Black's main response to this has been to play} (6. e3 {is also possible, transposing to the Meran variation.}) (6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bg5 {is also quite reasonable}) 6... dxe4 7. Nxe4 Nxe4 8. Qxe4 Bb4+ {with the intention of trading as many pieces as possible. We are forced to play} 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Nxd2 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4] where Black hasn't fully solved his problems.} O-O {and here I recommend going for} ({trying to solve the problem of space with} 10... c5 {is possible, but after} 11. dxc5 Qf6 12. Rb1 Nxc5 13. Qe3 $14 {white retains an edge. A possible line can be} b6 14. b4 Nd7 15. c5 $1 {[%csl Gc5] where we keep good chances due to the passed c-pawn.}) 11. Be2 $5 ({seems tempting, but after} 11. O-O-O c5 12. Nf3 Nf6 {black seems to be doing alright.}) 11... Re8 $5 {[%cal Re6e5]} (11... c5 12. dxc5 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4] gives us the typical spacial edge.}) 12. f4 $1 {the point behind our moves.} c5 13. O-O-O cxd4 14. Qxd4 $5 {[%csl Rc8,Rd7][%cal Gh1e1,Gd2f3,Rd2e4,Re4d6] white keeps some pressure due to the extra space and lead in development.}) (5... Bd6 {runs into} 6. Bg5 h6 {and now the simplest way to get an edge is} 7. Bxf6 $5 Nxf6 8. c5 $1 Be7 9. e3 {[%csl Gc5,Gd4,Ge3][%cal Gb2b4] with a good spacial edge.} c6 10. Bd3 O-O ({another tempting possibility is} 10... Nd7 11. O-O e5 {here, we need to be precise and trade knights with} 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Bxc5 14. Kh1 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4] so we can push f4 at the right time.} Qe7 (14... O-O 15. Rae1 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 15. Na4 $1 Bb6 16. Nxb6 axb6 17. f4 $14) 11. O-O b6 12. Na4 $14) (5... Be7 {is possible, but we get our desired QGD setup after} 6. cxd5 exd5 (6... Nxd5 7. e4 Nxc3 8. bxc3 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge4] gives us a better version of the Semi-Tarrasch with ...Nxd5.}) 7. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gh2h3,Ge2e3,Gf1d3] This setup is covered in great detail in Part I of the QGD series. We want to play e3-Bd3-h3-0-0 in some order.} c6 8. h3 O-O 9. e3 Re8 10. Bd3 Nf8 {this is Black's most natural move which we typically meet with} 11. O-O Ng6 (11... Bd6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Ne5 {[%cal Gf2f4] leads us to a Stonewall without the 'bad bishop'.}) 12. Be5 Bd6 (12... Nxe5 13. dxe5 $14 {[%csl Rh7]}) 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Rfb1 $14 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gb2b4,Ga2a4]}) (5... a6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Gh2h3,Ge2e3] White has a better version of the typical QGD lines.}) (5... dxc4 {the most critical move is covered from Chapter 10 onwards.}) (5... Bb4 {is covered in the next chapter.}) 6. cxd5 $1 {a typical move in such positions. We want to head to positions after} Nxd5 7. Nxd5 exd5 8. e3 $5 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5] where we claim that white retains an edge due to the isolated pawn in the centre.} Bd6 {the most active square for the bishop.} (8... Be7 {was tried in one of the games.} 9. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gf1d3] we are heading towards our desired setup.} O-O 10. Bd3 b6 (10... Nf6 11. Bb2 cxd4 12. Nxd4 $14 {[%csl Rd5]}) 11. Bb2 Bb7 12. O-O {[%csl Rb7,Rd5] These positions are quite comfortable for white. The combination of an isolated pawn on d5 and the bad bishop on b7 is not great for black.}) (8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 $14) 9. b3 O-O (9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 O-O 11. Bd3 $1 {transposes} (11. Bb2 $6 Ne5 $132)) 10. Bd3 h6 {played in the only game in the position. This allows us to get our desired setup with} (10... cxd4 $1 $146 {this novelty is black's strongest response in the position. We will not be able to take back on d4 with the bishop.} 11. Nxd4 Nf6 (11... Qh4 {is premature. After} 12. Nf5 Bb4+ 13. Kf1 $14 {[%cal Gc1b2] white has nothing to worry about.}) 12. O-O Bd7 13. Bb2 {with a slightly pleasant position for White. Black is doing fine with accurate play, but nevertheless, white keeps a better pawn structure.}) 11. O-O b6 12. Bb2 $14 {[%csl Rc8,Rd5][%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1,Ya2a4,Ya4a5,Gb2d4] where we keep the typical edge.} *

