{[%evp 0,29,19,34,29,0,-11,6,6,6,46,5,23,-25,15,4,5,-3,-12,4,4,-33,-21,98,86,81,71,60,60,60,60,76]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 (4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Qc2 c5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb8c6]}) 4... Nbd7 5. Qc2 Bb4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4][%cal Gd1c2,Rc7c5,Rd5c4,Yb8c6,Gb4c3] the point of deviation from the previous chapter. Black develops the bishop to the most active square. However,this allows us to play} (5... c6 {[%cal Rf8b4,Gc1d2]}) 6. g3 $5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yb8c6,Gd8d4] and get a better version of the Catalan. Black typically wants to play ...c5-Nc6 in these Catalan structures when white commits to early Qc2. However, since the knight is on d7, black cannot do so. starting with} O-O (6... dxc4 {another natural response.} 7. Bg2 c5 $5 {this is more challenging if black is able to play ...Nc6. With the knight being on d7, white isn't threatened seriously.} (7... b5 $6 8. Ne5 $16 {[%cal Gg2a8]}) (7... O-O 8. O-O c5 {transposes.}) (7... c6 8. O-O O-O {transposes.}) 8. O-O {[%csl Rc8,Gg2] These positions are quite pleasant and risk-free for White. White keeps an edge due to the much superior activity of the pieces.} cxd4 {the most natural response. However after} (8... O-O 9. Rd1 Qa5 10. Bd2 cxd4 11. Nxd4 {transposes.}) 9. Nxd4 {[%csl Gd4,Gg2] White can even stop memorizing here. The position is so much easier to play} O-O 10. Rd1 $5 {just bring all of your pieces into the game.} Qa5 (10... Qe7 11. a3 Ba5 (11... Bxc3 12. Qxc3 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Gg2][%cal Yc3c4]}) 12. b4 $1 $14 cxb3 (12... Bb6 13. Na4 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gc2c4]}) 13. Nxb3 {[%csl Ra5,Rb7]} Bb6 14. a4 $18 {[%cal Gc1a3]}) 11. Bd2 Qh5 12. Ne4 {[%csl Rc4,Rc8]} Bxd2 13. Nxd2 {[%cal Gd2c4]} Nb6 14. a4 $1 {[%csl Rb6]} e5 (14... a5 15. Nxc4 $16) 15. Nb5 $14 {[%cal Ga4a5,Yd2c4]}) (6... c6 7. a3 Be7 8. e4 {is a much better version of the 5...c6 line. After} dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 $14 {[%cal Ge7b4] Black cannot trade bishops with ...Bb4+.}) 7. Bg2 {black more or less needs to play} dxc4 (7... c6 8. O-O b6 (8... dxc4 9. Rd1 {transposes.}) 9. Rd1 Bb7 {is met with} 10. a3 Bxc3 11. Qxc3 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Gg2] where white enjoys a stable advantage of the pair of Bishops. With white's light-squared bishop being on g2, there are no problems in this position whatsoever.}) 8. O-O {[%cal Gf1d1,Ge2e4] retreating the bishop with} Be7 {makes sense. We can continue naturally with} (8... c6 {the most natural way of playing this position.} 9. Rd1 Be7 (9... b5 10. Ne5 $16) (9... Qe7 10. Ne5 $14) 10. a4 {transposes}) (8... a6 {doesn't help. We can play the desired} 9. Rd1 {with the intention of meeting} b5 $4 {with} (9... Rb8 10. Ne5 $16) 10. Ne5 $18) ({is met with thematic} 8... Rb8 $6 9. Rd1 b5 $6 10. Ne5 $16) 9. Rd1 c6 {and now stop black from pushing ...b5 with} 10. a4 $1 {after} a5 11. e4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4]} b6 12. Bf4 $14 {[%csl Rc4,Gd4,Ge4,Gf3][%cal Gc2e2,Gf3d2,Gd2c4,Gd4d5] white keeps the typical edge due to the extra space and lead in development.} *

