1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. Qc2 dxc4 {the point of deviation from the previous chapter. Black accepts the challenge head-on and grabs the pawn.} 6. e4 {we gain space in the center as usual} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] This is the most critical line after 5...dxc4. With the queen being on c2, the d4-pawn is slightly vulnerable.} (6... Nb6 {is covered in Chapter 12.}) 7. Bxc4 {and now black's most critical reply is} cxd4 {other moves are significantly weaker.} (7... a6 {allows us to get a central passed pawn with} 8. d5 $1 {black can try challenging this with} Nb6 (8... b5 $4 9. dxe6 $18) {but after} 9. b3 {white has a stable advantage. Note that taking everything on d5 with} exd5 10. exd5 $16 Nfxd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 {isn't great, and after} 12. O-O $18 {[%csl Rd5,Re8][%cal Gf1d1,Gc2e4,Gf3g5,Yf1e1,Gc1b2] Black is busted due to the multiple threats.}) (7... Nb6 $6 8. Bd3 cxd4 {runs into} 9. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5c7] we aren't afraid of} Bb4+ {and can safely play} 10. Kf1 $16 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Ge4e5,Ge8g8] with a huge advantage.}) 8. Nxd4 {and here we would cover all of black's responses except 8...Ne5 is the strongest for Black here.} Qc7 {[%csl Rc4] Black develops the queen and wants us to move our bishop back to a less active square} (8... Bc5 {is quite possible too. We can play} 9. Nf3 {looking to transpose to the line with 8...Qc7.} O-O (9... Ng4 {is a bit premature. After} 10. O-O {White has nothing to be afraid of. We can develop comfortably after} O-O 11. Bf4 $14 {[%csl Ra8,Gc4,Rc8,Gf4] with a pleasant position for White.}) (9... a6 10. O-O Qc7 11. Qe2 {transposes to the main line of the chapter.}) 10. O-O Qc7 {is met with the typical} 11. Qe2 {[%cal Ge4e5] where we try to claim that white remains better due to the extra space in the centre along with the lead in development. stopping e5. We can enter the following forced sequence with} Ne5 (11... a6 12. e5 $16) 12. Bf4 Bd6 13. Nb5 $1 Qxc4 14. Qxc4 Nxc4 15. Bxd6 $14 {where white remains better due to the activity of our pieces.}) (8... a6 {this is quite possible too. We can reply typically with} 9. O-O {where black has a few choices.} Bd6 $5 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc4b3,Yc8b7]} (9... Qc7 10. Qe2 {transposes to the line with 9..a6.}) (9... Ne5 {this looks tempting but we can go for the natural} 10. Rd1 $1 Bd7 (10... Nxc4 {runs into} 11. Nc6 Qc7 12. Rd8+ Qxd8 13. Nxd8 $18 Kxd8 14. Qd3+ {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ge4e5] where retains a significant material advantage.}) 11. Be2 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Gc1f4,Ge4e5] We'll play Bf4 next.}) (9... Nb6 10. Rd1 $1 $18 {[%cal Gd4e6]}) (9... b5 {is quite premature. We can now destroy the centre with} 10. Bxe6 {and after} fxe6 11. Nxe6 Qa5 ({or} 11... Qb6) {white has the strong} 12. Nd5 $18 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gd5c7,Ge6c7] with a decisive advantage.}) 10. Bb3 {we step out of the b5 threats.} b5 ({also natural is} 10... O-O {we would like to play Be3 here, but unfortunately, that runs into ...Ng4. Hence, the strongest move is} 11. h3 $1 {[%cal Gc1e3] preparing Be3. To stop that from happening, Black can play} Nc5 {Black can play} 12. Rd1 Qc7 {but after} 13. Nf3 {[%csl Ra8,Rc8][%cal Gc1g5] threatening Bg5, we keep an edge.}) 11. Rd1 $1 Qc7 (11... Qb6 12. a4 b4 13. a5 Qc7 14. Nce2 $14 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gc1e3] We keep an edge thanks to the activity of our pieces and the extra space. Note that} Bxh2+ $6 {runs into} 15. Kf1 Bd6 16. Ba4 O-O 17. Nc6 $18 {[%cal Gc6e7,Gc2c7] threatening Ne7, where black is gasping for air.}) 12. h3 {Black is struggling here, as} O-O {runs into} 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Nxe6 Qc6 15. Nxf8 Nxf8 16. Be3 $16 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gc3d5]}) (8... Bd6 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4] Although the bishop is active here, Black does not push our pieces away from the center. After} 9. h3 O-O 10. Be3 $16 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge3,Ge4] White keeps a healthy advantage.}) (8... Qb6 $6 9. Nf3 $14 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ge4e5]}) (8... Nb6 9. Bb5+ Bd7 {is a weaker version of the line with 8...Ne5. After} 10. O-O Rc8 11. Qe2 $14 {we keep a comfortable edge.}) (8... Ne5 {is the strongest reply for Black. This move is covered separately in the next chapter.}) 9. Qe2 $1 {[%csl Gc4] maintaining the active bishop.} (9. Bb3 $6 Bc5 $11) 9... Bc5 {the most critical move.} ({another natural looking move is} 9... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] intending b5. We can comfortably play} 10. O-O {[%csl Gc3,Gc4,Gd4,Re8,Rf8] where black needs to be a bit careful.} b5 (10... Bc5 11. Nf3 {transposes to the main line of the chapter.}) (10... h5 {this looks quite natural, but white can go for} 11. Bxe6 $1 fxe6 12. Nxe6 Qe5 13. Nxf8 Kxf8 14. f4 $16 {[%csl Rc8,Rd7,Rf8][%cal Ge4e5]}) (10... Ne5 11. Bb3 Bc5 12. Nf3 $14 {[%cal Gc1f4]}) 11. Bd5 $3 {[%csl Re8] the point behind our sequence.} exd5 (11... Rb8 {this is the comp's top choice} 12. Be3 {and black again has an uncomfortable position.} Bc5 (12... exd5 {runs into} 13. Rac1 Bc5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 O-O 16. b4 $18) 13. Bxe6 $3 fxe6 14. Nxe6 Qe5 15. Nxg7+ Kf7 16. Nf5 Bxe3 17. fxe3 Bb7 18. Ng3 $44 {[%csl Rf7] we keep great compensation thanks to the horrible black king.}) 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. exd5+ Ne5 {allows us to win the piece back with} (13... Qe5 14. Re1 Qxe2 15. Rxe2+ Kd8 16. Bf4 $16 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gd4c6]}) 14. Nc6 f6 15. f4 Bc5+ 16. Kh1 O-O 17. fxe5 fxe5 18. Be3 $14) (9... Be7 {runs into} 10. f4 $14) 10. Nf3 $5 {[%cal Ge4e5] we are threatening e5. Black now has two critical moves.} Ne5 {Black stops e5. However, after} (10... a6 $5 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 11. O-O {gives us a comfortable game. After} Bd6 (11... b5 12. Bb3 Bb7 {runs into} 13. e5 Ng4 14. Bf4 $16 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gh2h3]}) 12. Bb3 O-O 13. Bg5 {Black is under huge pressure. We are threatening Bxf6-e5.} b5 14. Rac1 Qb8 {and now after} 15. Bxf6 $5 {black is forced to play} gxf6 {and spoil the pawn structure. However, with} 16. Nd4 {[%cal Ge2h5] we are able to brew up a huge initiative on the kingside. Some sample lines-} Ne5 (16... Kh8 17. Qh5 $5) 17. Qh5 Qb6 (17... Bb7 18. Nd5 exd5 19. Rc3 Bc8 20. Bxd5 $5) 18. Rcd1 Kh8 19. Kh1 Ng6 20. Nce2 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5]}) (10... O-O 11. O-O {transposes.}) 11. Nxe5 Qxe5 {we can go for} 12. f4 {[%cal Ge4e5] threatening e5.} Qc7 {[%csl Re1] Black claims that we cannot castle anymore. However, because we have huge space in the centre, we can counter this easily.} (12... Qd4 {runs into} 13. e5 Nd5 14. Nb5 {where black is clearly under trouble.} Bb4+ 15. Kf1 Qb6 16. a3 $16 {[%csl Rd5,Rd6][%cal Gb5d6,Gc4d5,Gc1e3]}) 13. Bd2 {[%cal Ga1c1] threatening Rc1.} O-O 14. Rc1 {[%cal Gc1c7,Ge4e5]} Qd8 {the strongest response. Black drops the queen back to get out of the pin. After} (14... b6 15. e5 $14) (14... e5 {runs into} 15. f5 Rd8 16. g4 $14 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gc3d5]}) (14... Qe7 15. e5 $16 {gives us a great position.}) 15. e5 Nd5 16. Ne4 {Black has to play the accurate} Be7 ({Instead, the natural} 16... Bb6 {loses control of the d6 square. After} 17. Rf1 $1 {[%cal Gf1f3,Gf3h3] Black is about to come under attack. Note that} Qh4+ {is comfortably met with} 18. Kd1 Qxh2 19. Kc2 $18) 17. O-O *


