{Welcome to the eleventh chapter. In this chapter, we will be covering 11...Ne5 for black is the most critical response after 5.Qc2 dxc4 6.e4 c5.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. Qc2 dxc4 6. e4 c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Ne5 {Black attacks both of our minor pieces in the center, so we are forced to play} 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. O-O {and now black has quite some choices.} a6 $5 {played in both of the games that happened OTB in this variation.} ({another possible idea for Black is to play} 10... Bb4 {threatening ...Bxc3/...0-0. Here, we can go for} 11. a3 $1 {forcing Black to give up the bishop. After} Bxc3 12. Qxc3 {[%csl Gb5,Gc1] we now have the advantage of a pair of bishops.} O-O {and now it's important to preserve the bishop pair with} ({winning the pawn with} 12... Nxe4 {is impossible because of} 13. Qe3 $18) (12... Bxb5 $4 13. Nxb5 $18 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gc1g5,Gb5c7,Yb5d6,Gc3e5]}) 13. Be2 $5 Ng6 {[%cal Ge6e5] the strongest move in the position. Black threatens ...Nxe4/e5.} (13... Rc8 14. Qb3 $14 {remains pleasant for white.}) 14. Qe3 $5 {Black can equalize with concrete play, but nevertheless, white keeps some practical pressure in all positions.}) (10... Bc5 {is a bit weaker. We can consolidate our centre with} 11. Rd1 O-O {and now play} 12. Bf4 $14 {with an advantage thanks to the activity of the pieces.}) (10... Rc8 {is met with the thematic} 11. Rd1 a6 12. Bxd7+ Nexd7 13. Bg5 $14 {where white is exerting a lot of pressure.}) (10... Be7 {allows us to gain space with} 11. Rd1 O-O 12. Bxd7 Nfxd7 13. f4 $1 $14) (10... Bxb5 $6 11. Ncxb5 $16 {[%cal Gb5c7,Gf2f4]}) 11. Bxd7+ Nfxd7 {[%cal Gf8c5,Gd8h4] the point behind Black's play. Black wants to play ...Qh4 and create some chances on the kingside. Otherwise white remains better due to the extra space and activity.} 12. Rd1 Qh4 $5 {the critical response.} (12... Bc5 13. Bf4 $14 {gives us the position we are looking to get.}) (12... g5 $5 {is another interesting alternative. Black gains space and stops Bf4. Of course, this weakens the Kingside for Black.} 13. Nf3 $5 {we look to eliminate the active knight.} Nxf3+ 14. gxf3 {[%cal Gc1e3,Ga1c1]} Bg7 (14... Rc8 15. Be3 Bc5 16. Bxc5 Rxc5 17. Qa4 $14 {[%cal Gd1d4,Ga1d1] White retains an advantage thanks to the pressure on the d7-knight. We want to play Rd4/Rad1 next.}) 15. Be3 O-O {this allows us to exploit the weakesses on the kingside with} 16. h4 $1 {after} gxh4 17. f4 Qe7 18. Kh2 $6 {[%cal Gd1g1,Gg1g7,Ga1d1] white has great attacking prospects on the kingside.}) (12... Qc7 13. Bf4 $14) 13. Nce2 $146 {[%cal Gc1f4] the trickiest response in my opinion. The position now gets extremely sharp.} (13. Be3 Be7 14. Qe2 Rd8 15. f3 O-O {Black was doing fine in ½-½ (43) Narayanan,S (2663)-Eljanov,P (2697) Munich GER 2022}) 13... Ng4 {Practically the only move. Black has to enter the complications.} (13... g5 14. Ng3) (13... Bc5 14. Bf4 $14 {[%csl Rh4] white is able to comfortably hold the kingside and keep an advantage.}) 14. Ng3 $1 {[%cal Gg3h1] covering the important h1-square.} Qxh2+ (14... Bc5 {is comfortably met with} 15. h3 {where Black's attack is going nowhere. Note that} Nxf2 {is comfortably parried away with} 16. Qxf2 e5 17. Be3 $16) 15. Kf1 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gg3h1,Gd4f3,Gc2c7] even though we are a pawn down and Black has a queen on h2, it is Black who needs to be careful here. White has defended all the threats on the kingside comfortably while black's king in the centre is a bit vulnerable.} Qh4 $1 {Black's only defence. The queen needs to rush back to the rescue of the king.} (15... Nde5 $4 16. Qa4+ b5 17. Nxb5 $18 {[%csl Re8]}) (15... Be7 16. Nf3 {[%csl Rh2] Oops!}) 16. Nf3 {is the most testing line, in my opinion.} (16. Qc7 {is possible, but after} Rd8 $1 17. Nf3 Qe7 18. Qxb7 Qc5 {black is doing fine.}) 16... Qe7 {one of the two possible choices.} (16... Qd8 {is possible too. However, after} 17. e5 {[%cal Gc2e4] the lines are quite uncomfortable for black in a practical game. Some sample lines-} Qa5 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ga5b5]} (17... Qb6 18. Bf4 Qc6 19. Qe2 Qb5 20. Rac1 {[%cal Gc1c7,Gg3h5] white keeps tremendous pressure here. We want to penetrate onto the 7th file as well as play Nh5 next to stop f8-bishop from coming out.}) 18. b4 $1 {we don't mind opening up files!} Qb5+ (18... Bxb4 19. Rb1 $16 {[%csl Rb4,Rd7] Black has too many things too worry about.} Ndxe5 $6 20. Nxe5 Nxe5 21. Bb2 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gb2e5,Gb1b4]} Be7 22. Bxe5 Qxe5 23. Rxb7 $16 {[%csl Re7]}) 19. Kg1 {[%csl Rd7,Rg4] Black cannot castle comfortably due to the vulnerable knights.} Ndxe5 (19... h5 $5 20. Bg5 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gg3e4] gives us a huge initiative.}) 20. Nxe5 Nxe5 21. Bb2 Nc6 22. Ne4 {[%csl Ge4,Rf8,Rg7][%cal Ga2a4] we keep great attacking prospects.}) 17. Bf4 {we bring out our last minor piece into the game. White is doing great after all the normal moves and Black needs to play the concrete} Qc5 $1 18. Qe2 Qb5 {Black's problems are far from over as after} 19. Rac1 {[%cal Gc1c7] The position still looks uncomfortable.} e5 $5 {This looks tempting as we are forced to give up the bishop after} ({the natural} 19... Be7 {runs into the decisive} 20. Qxb5 axb5 21. Rc7 $16) 20. Be3 Nxe3+ 21. fxe3 {but black's problems are still not over.} f6 $1 {the only move to cleanly equalise. This is not easy to play.} (21... Nf6 {runs into} 22. Rc7 $1 {after which we keep an edge. A possible line can be} g6 23. Qxb5+ axb5 24. Rxb7 Bh6 25. Ke2 O-O 26. a3 $14 {[%csl Rb5,Re5]}) (21... Be7 $4 22. Nf5 $18) (21... Qxe2+ 22. Kxe2 f6 23. Rc7 Nc5 24. b4 Ne6 25. Rxb7 $14) 22. Rc7 $36 {the position is still not easy for Black as we have moves like Nf5 coming up next, but Black can defend with computer-like accuracy.} *

