{This is the final chapter on the 4...Nbd7 line for Black, where we cover 5...dxc4 6.e4 Nb6 and other options for Black.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. Qc2 dxc4 6. e4 Nb6 {this is a typical motif in such positions. Black wants us to give up the bishop with Bxc4. Instead, I recommend going for} (6... a6 $143 {is significantly weaker. After} 7. e5 Nd5 8. Bxc4 Nxc3 9. bxc3 $16 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge5] White has a great position thanks to the enormous spacial advantage. This position would have been file for Black without the dark-squared Bishops, but with them being on the board, this is far from fun.}) (6... b5 7. Nxb5 $14 {gives us a better version of the 4...dxc4 5.e4 b5 line, which we will be covering in the next chapter.}) 7. Be3 {[%cal Gf3e5] with the idea of playing Ne5-Nc4 next. This way, we retain the centre and the light-squared bishop.} Bb4 (7... Ng4 {is comfortably met with} 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. h3 Nf6 {and now we can even give the light-squared bishop with} 11. Bxc4 Nxc4 12. Qa4+ Bd7 13. Qxc4 Bc6 14. Qd3 $14 {and claim an advantage. Black does not have the advantage of bishop pair anymore, as the dark-squared bishops have been traded.}) (7... Bd7 {is possible. We can develop normally with} 8. Be2 {[%cal Gf3e5] with the idea to play Ne5 next.} (8. Ne5 c5 $1 {is black's point.} 9. dxc5 Qc7 $132) 8... Bb4 (8... Ng4 {is comfortably parried with} 9. Bf4 Bd6 10. e5 Bb4 11. Bg5 Be7 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Qe4 $14 {followed by Qxb7. White keeps an edge due to the better pawn structure.}) 9. Ne5 $1 $14) (7... Be7 8. Ne5 $14 {[%cal Ge5c4] we keep a comfortable edge after Nxc4.}) 8. Ne5 {we can go for the typical idea.} O-O (8... Bd7 9. Be2 {tr.}) 9. Be2 {Our idea is the obvious 0-0 followed by Nxc4. If we get that, white retains an edge due to the enormous special edge.} Bd7 {the computer likes this. Black's idea is to meet} (9... Qe7 {is inferior. We can try to grab the bishop with} 10. a3 {and if black retreats with} Ba5 {then the bishop is misplaced.} (10... Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 $16 {[%csl Rc4,Ge2,Ge3]}) (10... Bd6 {is comfortably met with} 11. Nf3 $1 {with the idea of meeting} e5 12. dxe5 Bxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 {with} 14. O-O-O {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gf2f4,Ge4e5] followed by f4.}) 11. f3 Bd7 12. O-O $14 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ge5c4,Ge2c4]}) 10. O-O {with} c5 {but after} ({the other moves are weaker.} 10... Rc8 {runs into} 11. a4 a5 12. Rfd1 Qe7 {and now we can even put pressure with} 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bh4 $14 {[%csl Re7,Rf6][%cal Gh4e7,Ge5c4]}) (10... Qe7 {is met with the thematic} 11. a4 a5 12. Rfd1 $1 h6 13. Nxc4 $14) {we can play} 11. dxc5 Qc7 12. cxb6 Qxe5 13. bxa7 $1 {with great pressure. Black can recover the pawn with} Bc5 {but we keep pressure with} 14. Qd2 {[%csl Rc4,Rd7] nevertheless.} *

