{Chapters 13-15 are dedicated to the Vienna variation arising after 4...dxc4. This chapter will cover the position after 5.e4 b5 !? arising from the Vienna variation.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 {Black gives up the centre but with} 5. e4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] we gain a massive centre. We will keep a huge advantage if we can retain the center, and hence Black needs to challenge the center.} b5 $5 {The modern way of playing these positions. Black gives up a pawn to get control of the light squares.} (5... Bb4 {is covered in the next couple of chapters.}) (5... c5 {allows us to keep a great position with} 6. Bxc4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Bc5 8. Be3 $14 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge3] where White is better due to the active pieces and the extra space.}) 6. e5 Nd5 (6... Nfd7 7. Nxb5 Nb6 {is the same thing.}) 7. Nxb5 Nb6 {Black's setup is usually Bb7-Nc6-Be7-Qd7-0-0. We would like to win the weak c4 pawn but it is difficult to do so without giving up the light-squared bishop.} 8. Be2 Nc6 {the most played move.} (8... Be7 {has no independent value. We should transpose sooner or later.} 9. Be3 Bb7 (9... Nc6 {transposes.}) 10. a3 Nc6 {transposes.} (10... O-O 11. Qc2 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gh2h4]} Nc6 12. Rd1 Na5 {transposes.})) 9. Be3 {we consciously delay 0-0 in these positions. This is done to keep the option of playing h4 in certain positions.} Be7 {Black's main move.} ({a tempting move is} 9... Bb4+ {forcing us to play} 10. Nc3 {which we don't mind at all. This retreat is something we wanted to play regardless of ...Bb4+. The bishop on b4 is misplaced, so we will kick it with a3 at the right time.} Ne7 $5 {Comp's top choice. Nevertheless, after} (10... O-O 11. O-O Rb8 {was played by Parham but after} 12. Na4 $14 {[%csl Rc4] white has a risk-free advantage.}) 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 Bb7 {and now the strong} 13. Bc1 $14 {[%cal Gf3d2,Ge2f3,Gc1a3] White has a quite comfortable position.}) (9... Bb7 {is another possible way of starting. Nevertheless, we can play the typical plan with} 10. Nc3 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gd1c2,Ga1d1] intending a3-Qc2-Rd1. We are delaying 0-0.} Be7 11. a3 O-O 12. Qc2 {Black now has a few choices.} f5 {the only independent try. Black prevents h4 but after} (12... Na5 13. Rd1 {transposes.}) (12... Qd7 {runs into} 13. h4 $16 {[%cal Gf3g5,Gc3e4] With threats of Ne4/Ng5 in the air. White won comfortably in 1-0 (39) Sarana,A (2654)-Tatarinov,D (2320) Chess.com INT 2020}) 13. exf6 Bxf6 14. Ne4 {Black has to accept an ugly position.} Ne7 (14... Bxd4 $4 15. Neg5 $18) 15. Nxf6+ gxf6 {Black wants to play ...Nf5 next, so we can go for the prophylactic} 16. g4 $1 {[%cal Gg4f5]} Kh8 17. Rg1 Qd6 18. Rg3 $14 {[%csl Rc4,Re6,Rf6,Rh7][%cal Gg3h3] with great practical chances.}) (9... Rb8 10. Nc3 Be7 11. a3 O-O 12. Qc2 {transposes.}) (9... Ba6 10. Nc3 Be7 11. a3 O-O 12. Qc2 Rb8 {transposes.}) 10. a3 {Controlling the b4 square. We are looking to play Qc2-Rd1-h4 next. Black now has quite a few choices.} Na5 $5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ga5b3]} (10... Bb7 {is met with the thematic} 11. Qc2 {now the only independent try seems to be} Qd7 {[%cal Gc6e5] with the idea of meeting} 12. Nc3 {with} O-O-O $6 {however, this is quite weak. White doesn't need to get afraid of ghosts and can play the natural} (12... Na5 {transposes.}) 13. O-O g5 14. Rfd1 {with a pleasant advantage. Note that} g4 {is comfortably met with} 15. Nd2 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Qxd4 17. Nxc4 $16 {[%csl Rb7,Rd4][%cal Gd4c5,Gb2b4,Gc4a5] after which the Black queen is under pressure.}) (10... O-O 11. Qc2 {typical} f5 $5 {tried by Xiong. Nevertheless, we keep a simple advantage after} (11... Rb8 {transposes.}) 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. O-O {due to the better pawn structure. The only important point is that we don't lose material after} a6 (13... Rb8 14. Rad1 $14) 14. Nc3 Nxd4 {as this is comfortably met with} 15. Bxd4 Bxd4 16. Rad1 {where we will recover the pawn and keep an edge due to the better pawn structure.} e5 (16... c5 17. Ne4 Qd5 18. Nxc5 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Rc4,Rd4,Re6]}) 17. Nxe5 $14) (10... Qd7 {is another possible move order. We typically respond to this move with} 11. Nc3 {getting the knight out of the danger zone. After} Na5 (11... Bb7 12. Qc2 {transposes.}) 12. Qc2 Bb7 {we have the strong} 13. Rd1 $1 {waiting for Black to castle.} f5 {typical but not strong.} (13... Bc6 {is met with the thematic} 14. h4 Rb8 {transposing to one of the critical positions.}) (13... O-O-O {is inferior. After} 14. O-O Kb8 15. Nd2 $16 {white keeps a risk free edge. White won comfortably in: 1-0 (34) Gledura,B (2644)-Smirin,I (2603) Saint Louis 2022}) (13... O-O 14. h4 $16 {[%cal Gh1h3,Gf3g5] gives us the position we were hoping to get.}) 14. exf6 gxf6 15. O-O $1 {We aren't afraid of ghosts as after} O-O-O {we can neutralize the active b7-bishop with} 16. Nd2 {[%csl Ra6,Rc4,Rc6,Re4,Re6] , after which black remains with quite a lot of light-squared weaknesses. A possible continuation can be} f5 17. Bf3 Rhg8 {where we can comfortably play} 18. g3 {Black's best bet here is} Bd6 {[%cal Gf5f4] intending f4. After} 19. Ne2 {[%cal Gb2b4] we are all set to open up the Queenside, so black needs to hurry with} h5 $5 {but this can be responded with} (19... Bxf3 20. Nxf3 Qa4 21. Qxa4 Nxa4 22. Rd2 $14 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gd2c2,Ge3d2] gives us a risk-free edge.}) 20. h4 $1 {[%cal Ge3g5,Gf3b7,Gf2f4] where after Bg5, we are able to stabilise everything. We will then begin to attack Black's weaknesses on the Queenside.}) (10... Rb8 {can be responded with the thematic} 11. Qc2 {one of the crucial positions of this system arises after} Qd7 (11... Ba6 {Was tried by Parham, but the bishop seems misplaced. After} 12. Nc3 {White keeps a comfortable position. Moves like} Na5 {don't haunt us, and we can respond with the typical} (12... O-O 13. h4) 13. Rd1 Qd7 14. h4 $5 {provoking h6.} h6 15. d5 $18 {where black is unable to play} Nxd5 {due to the threat of} 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. e6 $1 {the point. 17...Qxe6 runs into 18.Qa4+ while 17...fxe6 runs into 18.Ne5 followed by Qg6+.}) (11... Na5 12. Nc3 Bb7 13. Rd1 Qd7 {transposes.} (13... O-O {transposes.})) (11... O-O 12. Nc3 Na5 13. Rd1 Bb7 {transposes.}) 12. Nc3 Bb7 13. Rd1 Na5 {where we can play the thematic} 14. h4 {which black typically responds back by playing} Bc6 (14... h6 15. Rh3 $14 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gh3g3,Gf3d2] is quite comfortable for white. We want to play Rg3-Nd2 next.}) 15. h5 $1 {exploiting the fact that h6 is not possible.} Ba4 {was tried by Nakamaru and David Anton but after} (15... Na4 $4 {runs into} 16. d5 $1 exd5 17. h6 {where Black is busted.} g6 (17... gxh6 18. Nxa4 Bxa4 19. Qc3 $18 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Ge5e6]}) 18. e6 fxe6 19. Nxa4 Bxa4 20. Qc3 $18 {[%csl Rh8][%cal Gc3a5,Gc3h8] wins a piece.}) (15... h6 {weakens g6 thus allowing us to strike with} 16. d5 $1 exd5 (16... Nxd5 17. Bd2 $16 {[%csl Ra5,Rc4]}) 17. Bxb6 Rxb6 (17... axb6 18. Nd4 $16 {[%cal Ge5e6,Gd4c6,Gc4d5]}) 18. Nd4 Bb7 19. Nf5 $16 {[%cal Ge5e6,Ge1g1] with a huge initiative. Black cannot play} O-O {as it runs into} 20. Nxd5 $1 $18 Bxd5 21. Rxd5 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gf5e7]}) 16. Nxa4 Qxa4 17. Qe4 Nd5 (17... Qb3 18. Rd2 $16 {[%cal Gh5h6]}) 18. Rb1 $1 {white keeps a risk-free edge thanks to the attacking prospects on the kingside. Black misses the light-squared bishop dearly.} c3 {doesn't work due to} 19. b4 $18 {Chapter 31 Vienna e4 b5 [Kk]}) 11. Qc2 O-O 12. Rd1 {[%cal Gh2h4]} Bb7 13. Nc3 {and Black seems to be under pressure again.} Rb8 {very natural and typical response.} (13... Nd5 14. Bd2 Nb3 15. Bxc4 $14) (13... Qd7 {transposes.}) 14. h4 $1 h6 (14... f5 15. exf6 $16) (14... Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nd5 16. Be4 $14 {[%cal Gh1h3] gives white great attacking prospects on the kingside.}) (14... Qc8 15. Ng5 g6 16. h5 c5 17. Nxh7 {White won comfortably in 1-0 (26) Vidit,S (2727)-Garriga Cazorla,P (2472) Chess.com INT 2022}) 15. Rh3 {we are all set to start a kingside assault. Black needs to play} Nd5 {where we have the stunning} (15... Qd7 16. Nh2 $16 {[%cal Gh3g3,Gh2g4,Ge3h6]}) 16. Bxh6 $1 ({a safer way of playing this position is} 16. Bd2 $5 $14 {with a risk-free edge.}) 16... gxh6 17. b4 $3 {with the deep point of deflecting/capturing the c4 pawn so that the d3 square is accessible for our Bishop.} (17. Qc1 Kh7 $11) 17... cxb3 $4 {this natural move runs into} (17... Nc6 18. Bxc4 $18 {gives us a decisive edge.}) ({the computer prefers} 17... f5 {but after} 18. bxa5 $14 {White has absolutely no reason to complain about the position.}) 18. Qc1 $18 Kh7 19. Bd3+ $18 {with a mate to follow soon.} *

