1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 {the point of deviation from the previous chapter. This is the most popular move in the position. Black indirectly attacks the pawn on e4. Instead of defending it, the best move in the position is to sacrifice the pawn with} 6. Bxc4 Nxe4 7. O-O $1 {where we claim the lead in development fully compensates for the missing pawn. Black now has two important moves- 7...Nxc3 & 7...Nf6. In this chapter, we will be focusing on} Nxc3 (7... Nf6 {is covered in the next chapter.}) 8. bxc3 Be7 {the most played move. Black stops Ng5.} ({another possible continuation is} 8... Bd6 {placing the bishop on the most active square. However, this allows us to activate our knight with} 9. Ng5 h6 10. Qh5 O-O 11. Ne4 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gc1h6] where we retain good attacking chances. Black is forced to play} f5 {as otherwise Bxh6 would have been quite strong. We can respond by playing the natural} 12. Nxd6 cxd6 13. Re1 {[%csl Gc1,Gc4] where we keep a practical edge due to a safer king, better pawn structure and more active pieces. On top of that, White also has the advantage of the bishop pair.} Rf6 {computer's top choice.} ({it was also possible to play} 13... d5 {but after} 14. Bd3 {followed by Bf4-Re3-Rg3, white keeps initiative.} Qc7 $1 {stopping Bf4.} (14... Rf6 15. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Ge1e3,Gf4e5,Ge3g3,Ga1b1]}) 15. Re3 $1 $14 Rf6 (15... Qxc3 {is too greedy. White is better after} 16. Rb1 Bd7 17. Rg3 $1 $16 {[%cal Gc1h6,Gh5g6]}) 16. Rg3 Qf7 17. Qh4 $14) (13... Qf6 {is weaker. After the natural} 14. Bf4 d5 15. Bd3 Qf7 16. Qf3 {White keeps an edge by playing simple and strong moves. A possible line can be} Nc6 17. Rab1 Na5 18. Re3 Bd7 19. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Ge3g3,Gh2h4,Gf4e5]}) 14. Bf4 {However, white has a much easier game practically. A possible line is} d5 15. Bd3 Nc6 16. Rab1 $5 b6 17. Re3 Bd7 18. Rbe1 $14 {with a sound strategic edge for White.}) ({being greedy with} 8... Bxc3 {runs into} 9. Rb1 $1 {where Black is in huge trouble. Black cannot play} O-O {safely as after} 10. Rb3 Ba5 11. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Gc1,Gc4][%cal Gb3h3,Gd1h5] we have a decisive attack.}) {this is rarer than the mainline but is equally challenging. We want to play Rd1 next, stopping c5.} 9. Qe2 $5 (9. Ne5 O-O 10. Qg4 Nc6 $5 {is the main line of the system.}) 9... O-O (9... c5 {is premature. After} 10. Rd1 cxd4 11. cxd4 O-O 12. d5 $16 {[%csl Ra8,Rb8,Rc8] White keeps a huge edge thanks to the lead in development.}) 10. Rd1 $1 {Stopping Black from pushing c5. Black now has a few reasonable moves.} Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] preparing c5. We can respond by improving our knight with} (10... Bd6 $6 {is weaker, as after} 11. Bd3 $14 {[%cal Gc3c4,Gd3h7] we are not only threatening Bxh7, but also c4.}) (10... Bd7 {[%cal Gd7a4] is met with} 11. a4 Bc6 12. Ne5 $1 {[%csl Rb8][%cal Ge5f7,Ge5c6,Gd1d3,Gd3g3] where Black is unable to develop comfortably.}) (10... Nc6 11. Rb1 $1 $14 {leads to practical problems, as} b6 $4 {runs into} 12. d5 $18) 11. Ne5 $1 (11. Rd3 {is a possible alternative. Black's main response to this is} c5 12. Bf4 $5 {where Black needs to find} Qe8 $1 (12... Nf6 13. Re1 $14) {nevertheless, we keep some pressure with} 13. Ne5 Nb6 14. Rg3 $36) 11... Qe8 (11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qe8 {preparing ...b5. We should be prophylactic and play} 13. Bb5 $1 c6 14. Bc4 {[%csl Rc8] where we keep a comfortable advantage.} f5 (14... b5 15. Bd3 $16 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Ge2e4]}) 15. exf6 Bxf6 16. Ba3 $14 {[%csl Re6]}) (11... c5 {is possible, but after} 12. dxc5 $1 Qc7 13. Bf4 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Qxc5 15. a4 {[%csl Rc8] White keeps an edge due to the weak-c8 bishop.}) 12. Rb1 $1 {including the rook into the game. After} Nb6 13. Bb3 $146 {[%csl Re6,Rf7] White has a good initiative. Some sample lines!} Nd5 (13... f6 14. Nd3 $14 {[%csl Re6]}) 14. Bd2 b5 15. c4 bxc4 16. Bxc4 $1 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Rc7,Rc8,Rh7][%cal Gc4b5,Gc4d3,Gb1b3]} *

