1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bxc4 Nxe4 7. O-O Nf6 {The branching point of this chapter. Black decides to keep the knights on the board, thus keeping a defender on the kingside. However, we can be more positional this time and spoil Black's pawn structure with} 8. Qa4+ Nc6 9. Ne5 $1 {[%cal Ge5c6] threatening Nxc6. Black now has to choose between ...Bd6, ...a5 & ...Rb8.} Rb8 (9... Bd6 {was popular a while ago, but after} 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Qxc6+ Bd7 12. Qf3 {White has a comfortable edge.} h6 {stopping Bg5. Here I recommend going for} (12... O-O {runs into} 13. Bg5 {[%csl Rf6] where the f6-knight is a spot of concern. A possible line can be} h6 14. Bh4 Rb8 15. b3 Rb6 16. d5 $14 {where Black cannot capture back on d5 due to Nxd5. White remains better.}) 13. a4 {Keeping Nb5 ideas in the air. After} O-O 14. Rd1 $1 (14. b3 $5 {was a possible alternative too.}) 14... a5 15. b3 $14 {The problem of the backward pawn on b2 is now solved. We have multiple plans here- Nb5/d5 or Bd2/Bf4. White remains better thanks to the pawn structure.}) (9... a5 {isn't much different to the line with ...Bd6. We can respond similarly with} 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Qxc6+ Bd7 12. Qf3 {and after} O-O {we have the extra possibility of playing} 13. Bg5 Rb8 14. Rfd1 $14 {with an edge. One thing which you must be aware of is that after} h6 15. Bh4 Rb6 {you should play} 16. Qe2 {[%cal Gd1d3] stepping out of ...Qa8. White wants to play Rd3 next.} (16. Rac1 Qa8 {is what Black wanted.})) 10. Rd1 O-O {the critical response. However, after} (10... Bd6 {allows us to play} 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Qxa7 $1 {and after} Bd7 13. Bf1 O-O 14. Qa6 $14 {[%csl Ga2,Rc6,Rc7] we remain better.}) 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Qxa7 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7] we are better because of the weak pawns on c6 & c7.} Bd7 {the critical response. Black anticipates} (12... Bb7 {runs into} 13. Bg5 $14 {[%cal Ga7a4]}) 13. Qa4 {intending to meet this with} c5 {in hopes of getting a comfortable position after eliminating the weak pawn. Nevertheless, with} 14. Qc2 cxd4 15. Rxd4 $14 {[%csl Ga2] white remains better since we keep the outside passed pawn.} h6 {a tricky waiting move from Black. Black wants us to commit to a plan. Here I recommend playing} (15... Qe7 {runs into} 16. a4 $14) (15... Bc5 {was tried by Duda, but after} 16. Rd1 {[%cal Ga2a4] followed by a4. White keeps a pleasant advantage.} Qe7 (16... Ng4 $4 17. Ne4 $18) 17. a4 Bc6 {Black stops Ne4, but after} 18. h3 $14 {[%cal Ga4a5] we have nothing to be worried about.}) 16. h3 $1 $146 {Making an useful move. This stops ...Ng4. We are waiting for Black to play ...Qe7 so that we can play a4.} (16. a4 Bxa4 $1) (16. Bf4 Bc5 $1 17. Rdd1 Qe7 $11 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Ge6e5]}) 16... Qe7 ({another possibility is} 16... Ba4 17. Qd3 Bd7 {[%cal Gb4c5] but after} 18. Qe2 {we have slightly improved our Queen's position. After} Qe7 19. a3 $1 Bc5 20. Rd3 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc1b2,Gd3g3] white has a great position practically.}) 17. a4 $1 Bc5 18. Rd3 $14 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Gd3g3,Gc1e3] with good chances thanks to the outside passed pawn.} *

