{Welcome to the last chapter of this course. This chapter will cover 4...h6 or Black.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 h6 $5 {A recent trend. Black stops us from playing Bg5. While that is an advantage for black, White does get a better version of the Bf4 systems.} 5. Bf4 $5 {We bring out bishop to the optimal square. Note that we haven't started with 4.cxd5 as we would like to push c5 in some lines.} ({Just like Ding's 4.h3,} 5. h3 $5 {makes a lot of sense. The idea is to meet} Be7 {with} 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bf4 {getting a better version of the QGD cxd5 exd5 Bf4 lines. You are free to explore this on your own. The reason I didn't recommend this is that you would need to cover extra ground with 5...c5, 5...dxc4, 5...c6 and so on.}) ({playing in the QGD fashion with} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {allows Black to play} Bd6 {in one go.}) 5... Bd6 {the critical test.} (5... c6 $6 {is an inferior version of the Semi-Slav. After} 6. e3 Bd6 7. Ne5 $1 {White has a big advantage, say after} O-O 8. g4 $1 $16 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gg4g5]}) (5... a6 {is met with the typical} 6. cxd5 $5 exd5 (6... Nxd5 7. g3 {gives us a great position. We don't mind the trade with} Nxf4 8. gxf4 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Gf4][%cal Gf3e5,Ge2e3,Gf1g2] as this improves our central grip.}) 7. e3 Bd6 8. Be5 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gh2h3] followed by h3. Black cannot solve the problem of the bad bishop comfortably.} c6 (8... Be6 9. Qb3 $1 Ra7 10. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Ra7][%cal Gh2h3]}) 9. Bd3 Qe7 10. h3 $14) (5... Bb4 {is met with the typical} 6. cxd5 $1 Nxd5 {gives us a much better version of the Semi-Tarrasch after} (6... exd5 $5 {was tried by GM Idani. This is quite similar to Ragozin. However, Black has spent some time on 4...h6.} 7. e3 O-O 8. Qb3 $1 $146 c5 9. dxc5 {creating an isolated pawn. After} Nc6 10. Be2 Ne4 11. O-O $14 {White has a comfortable edge.}) 7. Bd2 O-O 8. e4 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Ba5 {We keep the dark-squared bishops on the board. You want to keep maximum pieces on the board in positions with extra space.} 10. Bc4 c5 {the most practical try. Black forces few exchanges.} (10... b6 {can be easily replied with} 11. O-O Nd7 12. Re1 Bb7 13. h3 $1 {where Black cannot play} c5 {since after} 14. d5 $14 {[%csl Gd5] White keeps a pleasant edge.}) 11. O-O cxd4 (11... Nc6 12. Rc1 cxd4 13. cxd4 Bxd2 14. Qxd2 $14 {doesn't change much.}) 12. cxd4 Bxd2 13. Qxd2 {Black has traded the dark-squared bishops and would have had a decent position if he had played b6 instead of h6. However, white has a much better position here due to the extra tempo.}) (5... dxc4 {can be met with} 6. e3 {after which Black usually goes for} Bd6 (6... a6 {is weaker. After} 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Be2 Bb7 {we have the strong} 9. Ne5 $1 {[%cal Ge2f3] with a bid advantage. We are not afraid of} Bxg2 {as after} 10. Rg1 Bb7 11. Bf3 {Black is busted because of the weak light squares.}) (6... Nd5 {can be met with the typical} 7. Bxc4 Nxf4 8. exf4 {[%csl Gd4,Gf4][%cal Gg2g3,Gd1e2,Ge1g1] where White remains better because of more space and the lead in development.}) 7. Ne5 $1 {our typical response. White remains better after} Nd5 8. Bxc4 Nxf4 9. exf4 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Gc4,Gd4,Ge5,Gf4][%cal Ge1g1]}) 6. Qc1 $5 {a very rare an interesting try. We are waiting for black to castle.} O-O {the most natural response.} (6... a6 {can be met with} 7. c5 $1 {with a comfortable edge. Usually the trade with} Bxf4 8. Qxf4 $14 {isn't great, but with the Queen on f4, it's a different story altogether. A possible line is} b6 9. cxb6 cxb6 10. Rc1 Bb7 11. e3 Nc6 12. Bd3 $14) ({the natural} 6... c5 {is premature. We can exploit this by playing} 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. dxc5 Qxc5 9. cxd5 $16 {where Black has no satisfactory response. The critical point is that both} Nxd5 ({or} 9... exd5) {runs into} 10. Nxd5 $18) ({trying to develop the c8-bishop with} 6... b6 {is the best reply for Black. Here, I recommend to for} 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. cxd5 $1 {where Black's best reply is to play} Nxd5 $1 (8... exd5 9. e3 $14 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gf1d3,Gc3b5] gives us a very comfortable game.These structures are quite pleasant for White.}) 9. g3 $5 {[%cal Gf1g2] Fianchettoing the bishop makes a lot of sense here. Black cannot kill the pressure yet due to the lack of development. A possible line is} O-O 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. O-O Rc8 12. Rd1 {where Black is still unable to push c5 cleanly. After} Nd7 13. Ne1 Nxc3 14. Qxc3 Bxg2 15. Nxg2 $14 {White keeps a tiny pull.}) 7. g4 $1 {The point behind our play. We want to smash open the kingside. This has been played only in a single game (which was played online, too) and thus carries great practical value.} Ne4 $1 {Counterattack is the best defence.} ({other moves are weaker. After} 7... Bxf4 8. Qxf4 Nc6 9. g5 {We have a huge attack. A possible line is} hxg5 10. Nxg5 Qd6 11. Qh4 Ne7 12. e3 Nf5 13. Qh3 $14 {[%cal Gh1g1] Where Black's king feels quite exposed.}) (7... dxc4 8. g5 hxg5 9. Bxg5 $14 {[%cal Gh1g1] Is extremely dangerous for black.}) (7... Nc6 {can be met with} 8. g5 $14 {or the more extravagant} (8. Bxh6 $5)) (7... c6) 8. h4 $1 $146 {We don't need to stop and can continue attacking!} (8. Rg1 $5 {tried by Sarana is a decent alternative. 1-0 (56) Sarana,A (2693)-Svane,R (2641) Chess.com INT 2023}) 8... Nc6 {Principled. Black puts pressure against our centre.} ({exchanging pieces with} 8... Nxc3 {doesn't solve the problem entirely.} 9. bxc3 c5 {the most principled response.} (9... Bxf4 10. Qxf4 $14 {[%cal Gg4g5]}) (9... dxc4 {runs into} 10. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 11. Qxh6 f6 12. Rg1 Qe7 13. e4 Qg7 14. Qe3 $40 {[%cal Gf1c4,Gg4g5] where Black's king is feeling the heat.}) 10. g5 $1 h5 {it seems like the attack has stopped and thus Black should be alright but after} 11. Bg2 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5,Gf4,Gg2][%cal Gg2d5] we still retain positional pressure.} Nc6 (11... cxd4 12. cxd4 $14 {[%cal Gc4c5]}) (11... dxc4 12. O-O Nc6 {looks tempting, but White has the cunning} 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Qa3 $1 {where we keep some pressure after dxc5. Black cannot play} b6 {due to the threat of} 15. dxc5 Qxc5 16. Qxc5 bxc5 17. Ne5 $1 $18) 12. O-O b6 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Rd1 $5 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5][%cal Gc3c4,Gg2a8,Gf4d6] with pressure due to the weak central pawns.}) (8... c5 {runs into} 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. g5 h5 {and now we can switch gears with} (10... hxg5 11. hxg5 $16 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gh1h8,Gh1h4,Gh4e4] is quite dangerous.}) 11. Bg2 $1 {and after} cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nxc3 13. Qxc3 $14 {White keeps an edge.}) 9. Bxh6 $5 {this looks extremely scary for Black in a practical game.} (9. Bg2 $5) 9... gxh6 10. c5 $1 {the important intemezzo. Black cannot play Qh6 Qf6 anymore.} Be7 (10... Kh7 {runs into} 11. cxd6 Qxd6 12. g5 $1 {Where white keeps attacking chances alive.}) (10... Nxc3 $4 11. Qxh6 $18 {[%cal Gf3g5]}) 11. Qxh6 {[%cal Gc3e4,Gf3g5] the threat of Nxe4-Ng5 looks decisive, but black has} Re8 {coming to the rescue. Black vacates the f8-square for the king. White should start a forced sequence with} 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Ng5 Bxg5 14. hxg5 Qxd4 15. Bg2 {where only} Qg7 {holds for black} (15... Qxb2 16. Qf6 Qxf6 17. gxf6 $18 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gg2e4,Gh1h5] gives us a decisive advantage. Black's king is very weak.}) 16. Qf6 $5 {and here after} Ne5 $1 {forcing us to play} (16... Qxf6 17. gxf6 $18 {[%cal Gh1h5,Gg2e4,Ge1c1]}) 17. Bxe4 Nxg4 18. Qxg7+ Kxg7 19. c6 b6 20. Rh7+ Kf8 21. Rd1 $44 {Black is doing fine. We still retain some pressure. Black must be extremely precise here, so I fancy white's chances in a practical game.} *

